                <p>* During the period of military occupation (from the time of cessation of
                    hostilities to the signing of the Peace Treaty) Foreign Service Officers
                    assigned to Tokyo were given a diplomatic rank of Counselor, First, Second or
                    Third Secretary in order that they might have added prestige in dealing with the
                    military and foreign officials. Effective on the date of the signing of the
                    Peace Treaty with Japan, Apr. 28, 1952, these officers were assigned to Tokyo in
                    a full diplomatic capacity.</p>
